cience provide ethnographic insights as they investigate the presentation and generation of panic disorder in various cultures. The first available work with a focus on the historical and cross-cultural aspects of panic disorders, this book presents a fresh opportunity to reevaluate Western theories of panic that were formerly taken for granted.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCultural psychiatry. 0aEthnopsychology. 0aMedical anthropology. 0aPanic disordersvCross-cultural studies. 0aPanic disordersxCross-cultural studies. 0aPanic disordersxDiagnosisxHistory. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh1 aGood, Byron J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHinton, Devon E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477111540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804771115423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804771115.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles